   "source": [
    "# Mastering PostgreSQL with Python (Psycopg3)\n",
    "\n",
    "This tutorial covers the transition from basic SQL execution to high-performance data engineering patterns using `psycopg`, the modern PostgreSQL adapter for Python.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Core Concepts Covered:\n",
    "1. **Modern Connectivity**: Using Connection Pools.\n",
    "2. **Schema Design**: DDL and Relationships.\n",
    "3. **Performance**: Atomic `COPY` vs slow `INSERT`.\n",
    "4. **NoSQL Power**: Querying `JSONB` fields.\n",
    "5. **Transactions**: Ensuring ACID compliance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# 1. Environment Setup\n",
    "# 'psycopg[binary]' includes the C-extensions for maximum speed\n",
    "%pip install \"psycopg[binary]\" pandas"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Establishing a Robust Connection\n",
    "We use context managers (`with` statements) to ensure connections are closed even if errors occur."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    import psycopg
    from psycopg import sql
    import json

    # Configuration Dictionary
    DB_CONFIG = {
        "host": "localhost",
        "dbname": "postgres",
        "user": "postgres",
        "password": "your_password",
        "port": 5432
    }

    def get_conn():
        return psycopg.connect(**DB_CONFIG)

    print("Setup complete. Ready to connect.")
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Schema Design\n",
    "We will create a relational structure: **Users** and **Orders**. Note the use of `JSONB` in the orders table for unstructured metadata.\n",
    "\n",
    ""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "with get_conn() as conn:\n",
    "    with conn.cursor() as cur:\n",
    "        # Create Users Table\n",
    "        cur.execute(\"\"\"\n",
    "            CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS users (\n",
    "                user_id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n",
    "                username TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n",
    "                email TEXT NOT NULL\n",
    "            );\n",
    "        \"\"\")\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Create Orders Table with JSONB\n",
    "        cur.execute(\"\"\"\n",
    "            CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS orders (\n",
    "                order_id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n",
    "                user_id INTEGER REFERENCES users(user_id),\n",
    "                item TEXT,\n",
    "                details JSONB\n",
    "            );\n",
    "        \"\"\")\n",
    "        conn.commit()\n",
    "print(\"Tables created successfully.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. High-Performance Bulk Loading\n",
    "Standard `INSERT` statements are slow for large datasets because they require a round-trip to the server for every row. The `COPY` protocol is the professional standard for speed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "users_to_add = [\n",
    "    (\"dev_user\", \"dev@example.com\"),\n",
    "    (\"data_sci\", \"data@example.com\"),\n",
    "    (\"dba_admin\", \"admin@example.com\")\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "with get_conn() as conn:\n",
    "    with conn.cursor() as cur:\n",
    "        # The 'COPY' method for lightning fast inserts\n",
    "        with cur.copy(\"COPY users (username, email) FROM STDIN\") as copy:\n",
    "            for user in users_to_add:\n",
    "                copy.write_row(user)\n",
    "    conn.commit()\n",
    "print(\"Bulk insert completed using COPY.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Querying JSONB Data\n",
    "PostgreSQL allows you to query inside JSON strings using specific operators like `->>` (extract as text) or `?` (contains key)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Insert complex JSON data\n",
    "order_data = (1, \"Laptop\", json.dumps({\"specs\": {\"ram\": \"32GB\", \"cpu\": \"M3\"}, \"warranty\": \"2 years\"}))\n",
    "\n",
    "with get_conn() as conn:\n",
    "    with conn.cursor() as cur:\n",
    "        cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO orders (user_id, item, details) VALUES (%s, %s, %s)\", order_data)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Querying specifically for 32GB RAM within the JSONB column\n",
    "        cur.execute(\"\"\"\n",
    "            SELECT item, details->'specs'->>'cpu' as processor\n",
    "            FROM orders\n",
    "            WHERE details->'specs'->>'ram' = '32GB';\n",
    "        \"\"\")\n",
    "        print(\"Query Result:\", cur.fetchone())\n",
    "    conn.commit()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Transactions & Error Handling\n",
    "A transaction ensures that either all operations succeed, or none do. This is critical for financial or related data updates.\n",
    "\n",
    ""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "try:\n",
    "    with get_conn() as conn:\n",
    "        with conn.cursor() as cur:\n",
    "            # Start of atomic block\n",
    "            cur.execute(\"UPDATE users SET email = 'new@example.com' WHERE user_id = 1\")\n",
    "            \n",
    "            # Simulate an error\n",
    "            # raise ValueError(\"Simulated failure!\")\n",
    "            \n",
    "            cur.execute(\"DELETE FROM orders WHERE user_id = 999\") # Non-existent ID\n",
    "            \n",
    "            conn.commit()\n",
    "            print(\"Transaction committed successfully.\")\n",
    "except Exception as e:\n",
    "    print(f\"Transaction failed! Rolling back changes. Error: {e}\")"
   ]
  }
